         Forgive my question in this matter.  I realize this is probably a common thread, but I'm not really a necromancer.  I'm a cleric with a necromancer twink (Which I play badly, I'll admit).</P><P>My question is... you cite that HP are more important than mana because hit points allow you to create mana, but even the highest level lich spells are below a 1:1 ration, correct?  If this is the case, then you're actually trading more hit points to get less mana, especially if you factor in the cost of lifetapping those hit points back up, and no matter how much you work that math, you end up better off just having a sufficient pool of hit points to work your liche and then focusing on mana entirely.  </P><P>For example, if at level 53 I transfer 720 hit points into 450 mana (Lich, which I have listed at 20 mana for 32 hit points or .625 ratio), then spend 360 mana casting BOD to heal those hit points back with BOD, then my net gain is only 90 hit points over three and a half minutes or so.  My standing regen with KEI should net me more than that, shouldn't it?  I realize that I've dealt some damage to the mob in exchange for those 90 hit points and that specialization will reduce my costs somewhat, but for the additional mana I could probably drop BOD for a more efficient DOT.</P><P>Am I missing something here?  Are your mana conversion spells actually greater than a 1:1 ratio?  When I'm playing my necro I know that it feels like I'm actually gaining more mana than that, but I haven't done any hard testing. I apologize if I've missed an article somewhere that details your actual mana transfer effiviency.  I'd be interested in seeing one.</P><P>Borick Ascid<BR>High Priest of Brell<BR>Noble Blade<BR>The Rathe</P><P>Ervil Kenervil<BR>53 Gnome Necro</P><P><BR> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
